qas.question: Who claims that the list of nutrients that humans require is incomplete?
What is the other category of nutrients that people require other than micronutrients?
What is notable about cellulose in humans?
What else, other than antioxidants, helps protect body systems?
In which year were nutrients categorized into their two respective categories?

context: The list of nutrients that people are known to require is, in the words of <a0_0>Marion Nestle<a0_0/>, "almost certainly incomplete". As of <a4_0>2014<a4_0/>, nutrients are thought to be of two types: <a1_0>macro-nutrients<a1_0/> which are needed in relatively large amounts, and micronutrients which are needed in smaller quantities. A type of carbohydrate, dietary fiber, i.e. <a2_0>non-digestible<a2_0/> material such as cellulose, is required, for both mechanical and biochemical reasons, although the exact reasons remain unclear. Other micronutrients include antioxidants and <a3_0>phytochemicals<a3_0/>, which are said to influence (or protect) some body systems. Their necessity is not as well established as in the case of, for instance, vitamins.
